      "\n",
      "--- Q26: Architectural ACID Robustness Evaluation ---\n",
      "Theoretical Framework Analysis:\n",
      "* Atomicity: Guarantees that an entire transaction occurs as a single unit of work—either every single statement succeeds, or the database is rolled back to its exact starting state. (e.g., In a bank transfer, deducting money from Account A without depositing it into Account B is completely blocked).\n",
      "* Consistency: Enforces that any transaction moves the database from one valid state to another, preserving all strict structural schema rules, constraints, and relationships.\n",
      "* Isolation: Ensures that concurrently running operations cannot see each other's uncommitted intermediate data states, preventing race conditions or dirty reads.\n",
      "* Durability: Guarantees that once a transaction commits, its modifications are written permanently to non-volatile disk storage. The data will survive even a sudden system crash or power loss.\n",
